<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="393" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,297,2016]" pageId="1" pageNumber="393">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,1774,1800]" pageId="1" pageNumber="393">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet is allusive to the stain of white setae covering the lateral tubercles of the pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[239,307,1809,1836]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–7" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1875,1900]" captionTargetBox="[188,1396,237,1850]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[187,1400,237,1850]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–7. Plistonax albituberculatus Silva Júnior &amp; Souza sp. nov., holotype male.1. Dorsal habitus; 2. Ventral habitus; 3. Lateral habitus; 4, Head, frontal view; 5. Prothorax, dorsal view; 6. Labels; 7. Elytra, detail of punctation and setae." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3772443" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3772443/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="393">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
), which is the main feature that distinguishes 
<taxonomicName authority="Júnior &amp; Haseyama &amp; Souza, 2019" authorityName="Júnior &amp; Haseyama &amp; Souza" authorityYear="2019" box="[827,1123,1809,1835]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Plistonax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="393" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albituberculatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[827,1123,1809,1835]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="393">Plistonax albituberculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1130,1220,1810,1836]" pageId="1" pageNumber="393">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1130,1220,1810,1836]" pageId="1" pageNumber="393" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
from other species of the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="394" pageId="1" pageNumber="393" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,297,2016]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1436,153,215]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="394" pageId="1" pageNumber="393">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,1881,1908]" pageId="1" pageNumber="393">Comments.</emphasis>
The new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Zajciw, 1964)" baseAuthorityName="Zajciw" baseAuthorityYear="1964" box="[667,1136,1881,1908]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Plistonax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="393" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bialbomaculatus">
<emphasis box="[667,966,1881,1907]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="393">Plistonax bialbomaculatus</emphasis>
(Zajciw, 1964)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Martins &amp; Galileo, 2006" authorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" authorityYear="2006" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Plistonax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="393" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rafaeli">
<emphasis box="[1188,1375,1881,1907]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="393">Plistonax rafaeli</emphasis>
Martins &amp; Galileo, 
<quantity box="[324,380,1917,1943]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0952399999999995" pageId="1" pageNumber="393" unit="in" value="2006.0">2006</quantity>
</taxonomicName>
in general appearance, body size, and by having elytral apex truncate and median-basal crests reaching approximately half of the elytra. However, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Zajciw" baseAuthorityYear="1964" box="[757,975,1953,1979]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Plistonax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="393" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bialbomaculatus">
<emphasis box="[757,975,1953,1979]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="393">P. bialbomaculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Martins &amp; Galileo" authorityYear="2006" box="[1034,1139,1953,1979]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Plistonax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="393" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rafaeli">
<emphasis box="[1034,1139,1953,1979]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="393">P. rafaeli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are only known from the Amazon region. 
<taxonomicName authority="Júnior &amp; Haseyama &amp; Souza, 2019" authorityName="Júnior &amp; Haseyama &amp; Souza" authorityYear="2019" box="[341,637,1989,2015]" class="Insecta" family="Cerambycidae" genus="Plistonax" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="393" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albituberculatus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[341,637,1989,2015]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="393">Plistonax albituberculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[645,735,1990,2016]" pageId="1" pageNumber="393">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[645,735,1990,2016]" pageId="1" pageNumber="393" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be differentiated from all species of the genus by having, together, the lateral tubercles of the pronotum and tarsomeres I and V densely covered by white setae, and abdominal tergite V without sexual dimorphism related to its length.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
